@ovcharenko to enforce the state you want, where state = ports this machine listens on. In a real world situation if it needs to enforce at all you have some other issue to deal with (intrusion, policy violation etc), so as mentioned the fact of it is probably more interesting - but I figured in writing a module for a system like Ansible that enforcing your desired state is always preferable than just reporting it, as an option (in this case, by default - could modules be check mode by default?). After all, any state change Ansible makes is arguably prone to modification by some other process at almost any point in time (granted ports can be in a fairly ephemeral state).

Perhaps a killer combo is feeding a violation into a firewall role? could Ansible do this?

What about `listen_port_policy` or `listen_port_whitelist` ?

@ndavison I contest that it enforces anything. It kills a process, but if I were to write some backdoor I would ensure it restarts if it gets killed. If this was a system service, a reboot would activate it again.

A much better approach is to configure the firewall and report if any unexpected firewall changes have happened. But killing processes is never the solution. We have a saying in Dutch "dweilen met de kraan open" which translates to "mopping with the tap open". The solution is not "to mop" but turn the water off.

Reporting strange things (like ports that are listened on and shouldn't be listened on) is valuable, but someone will have to modify the configuration (or clean the system if it were compromised), killing the process is never a remediation. So I am concerned that this module would promote a bad practice and that is for me a reason to reject this module.

@samdoran, I agree with the idea of being able to pass more than one command at a time. Please keep in mind that all connections are local (no ssh connections/copying to remote hosts) and that for every command a URI has to be built and sent across (and data sent back), regardless of how many commands are passed per invocation, so even though passing multiple commands is more aligned with Ansible's philosophy for efficiency, I'm not sure performance will be greatly improved.

I need to think more about how returned data will be stored (currently separate files per command), error handling (should it just exit if a command fails or keep going?) and possibly other considerations that may pop up, as the intent was always to pass one command at a time.

Thank you for your review, it has made me think of the possibilities :)

